<DOC><DOCNO> AP890307-0165 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-07-89 1811EST</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-Obit-Pelat     03-07 0279</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Obit-Pelat,0286</SECOND><HEAD>Friend of President Charged In Trading Scandal Dies</HEAD><DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Roger-Patrice Pelat, a longtime friend of PresidentFrancois Mitterrand, died Tuesday in a hospital three weeks after hewas charged in an insider trading scandal that has embarrassedFrance's Socialist government. He was 70.   Pelat was admitted to the American Hospital in the Paris suburbof Neuilly on Feb. 27 suffering a pulmonary embolism and died of aheart attack Tuesday, a spokeswoman said. She spoke on condition ofanonymity in keeping with hospital policy.   The French news agency Agence France-Presse said Mitterrand wentto the hospital after hearing of Pelat's death.   Pelat and Mitterrand met in a German prisoner-of-war camp in 1940and later fought together in the French Resistance.   Over national television on Feb. 12, Mitterrand defended Pelat asa man of courage and integrity, but said if Pelat were found guiltyof an offense, ``then in my role as president I would not be able tomaintain the same kind of friendship I have had with him for solong.''   Four days later, Pelat was charged with receiving insiderinformation that allowed him to buy shares of the U.S. companyTriangle Industries Inc. shortly before the French state-ownedaluminum manufacturer Picheney SA offered a much higher price lastyear in a successful takeover.   Pelat and his family sold their shares after the price soared,making a profit of about $350,000.   Five others also were charged by an investigating magsitrate withreceiving insider information or with insider trading. Either chargecarries the same maximum penalty of two years in prison and a fineof up to four times the amount of illegal profits.</TEXT></DOC>